{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_immokalee_ver01/data/sn95047334/00529042474/1958041701/0230.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWELVE\nBEHIND THE\nSCENES IN\nAMERICAN BUSINESS\nBy REYNOLDS KNIGHT\n'^ew York, April 14 Are\n^ou a member of the Upturn-by-\nMidyear club or the Some-Time-\nAfter-Labor-Day clan?\nYour own estimate of the time\nit will take business to turn the\ncorner depends, of course, on\nhow you\u2019ve been treated by the\nrecession. But there are many\nmore hopeful signs today than\nthere were even a month or six\nweeks ago.\nA survey of 100 company presi\ndents mostly among the 400\nlargest industrial firms shows\nthat 80 per cent anticipate an\nupturn in the economy sometime\nin \u20195B and half of this group pre\ndict the fourth quarter as the\nturning point. There are some,\nhowever, who feel that business\nis already on the upswing, even\nthough it won\u2019t show up statis\ntically for three or four months.\nHopeful forecasts for better\nbusiness this year have been\nmade by some people in the fur\nindustry, the toy trade, the syn\nthetic carpet business, and even\nby some appliance makers one\nof the really sick businesses of\nthe last few months. Mail-order\nhouses report a spurt in catalog\nsales, indicating that buyers are\n.bunting bargains.\nRecession Antidote Indica-\ntions that enterprise in develop\ning new recession-fighting pro\nducts and new techniques for\n1 selling them can offset the ef\nfects of recession come from the\nSheaffer Pen Company. Its new\nLady Sheaffer' line of fountain\npens, just introduced, has met\nwith enthusiastic acceptance and\npromises to give the company a\nbigger sales boost than the Snork\nel fountain pen introduced in\nbooming 1952.\n\u201cThe influx of retailers\u2019 orders\n\u201efor this new kind of pen, even\n\u00bbbefore it\u2019s advertised and offer\n*ed to the public, seems to show\n,that gloom talk hasn\u2019t dampen-\n7/J& 7\n/SW\nSUBER JOHNSON CO.\n315 W. Jefferson Quincy\nFULLY EQUIPPED MERCURY\nPRICED LOWER THAN\ni 42 MODELS OF THE\n\u201cLOW-PRICED 3\u201c\n14*1 T^y^^l^oof Soldi\nOur price for this all-new Mercury includes:\nAUTOMATIC TRANSMISSION HEATER\nRADIO POWER STEERING WHITEWALLS\nGAS-SAVING V-8 ENGINE\nHUGE TRADE-IN ALLOWANCES NOW!\nHURRY! OFFER UNITED!\nMERCURY/58\nFLETCHER TRACTOR CO.\nChattahoochee Highway Quincy. Florida\ned merchants\u2019 confidence in the\nconsumer goods market,\u201d said\nPresident Walter A. Sheaffer 11.\n\u201cApparently, with national sav\nings and personal income still at\nclose to all-time highs, aggres\nsive retailers are not passing up\nhot items that have quality plus\nmerchandising appeal.\u201d\nIn addition to being a new\nkind of pen, the Lady Sheaffers\nare opening up new sales outlets\nfor pens, he explained. They will\nbe sold, in many cases, at cos\nmetic counters, costume jewelry\ncounters, boutique shops and\ngift counters as well as the ac\ncustomed stationery departments\nand pen counters.\nThings to Come A flower\ngarden that comes in a roll is\nsimply unrolled on a prepared\nflower bed and watered in the\ncustomary way; the seeds cannot\nwash or blow away and the\nwadding holding them finally\ndisintegrates to fertilize the soil\nA new cash register auto\nmatically, computes and dispens\nes the correct amount of change\ndue a shopper Paint-brush\ncleaning is made easy by a spin\nning device that comes in two\nmodels, electric powered and\nhand-operated.\nAutomated Factory The na\ntion\u2019s first all-electronically con\ntrolled line of machine tools\nliterally a \u201cpush-button factory\u201d\nis expected to speed up\n\u201ccrash\u201d development programs\nof the type the United States is\nnow pursuing in guided missiles.\nThat is the belief of Hughes\nAircraft Company officials who\nrecently unveiled a prototype\nsystem that makes available for\nthe first time the economies of\n\u201cDetroit-type\u201d mass production\ntechniques in the area of small\nlot production which now con\nstitutes most of the machining\ndone by American industry.\nHughes officials explained that\nsuch a system makes it possible\nto store production know-how on\na tape for use subsequent to the\nmain production run or for com\nmunication to other defense man\nufacturers. The system translates\na blueprint into finished \u201chard\nware\u201d In a minimum amount of\ntime. The human operator on the\nmachine tool line needs only to\nplace unmachined castings on\nthe line and 'remove finished\nparts and even this operation\ncan easily be made automatic.\nRemember \u2018Scrip?\u2019 Anyone\nwho thinks today\u2019s economic\nnews is bad probably is too\nyoung to remember those dark\ndays of 1933 25 years ago.\nWhen the nation\u2019s banks were\nclosed on March 4, no one knew\nhow long the bank holiday\nwould last.\nMany business firms hastily\nprinted \u201cscrip\u201d actually I. O.\nU.\u2019s to pay their employes.\nRetail establishments honored\nthe scrip almost without ques\ntion. Clearing houses in many\ncities authorized the printing of\nhundreds of millions of dollars'\nworth of scrip for use as interim\nlegal tender. Working overtime,\npresses ran off great stacks, of\nthe paper money and delivered\nit under armed guard.\nEmergency legislation by Con\ngress paved the way for banks\nto reopen on March 13, so most\nof the scrip stayed in bank\nvaults. Eventually, the unofficial\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES, QUINCY, FLORIDA, THURSDAY, APRIL 17, 1958\ncurrency was incinerated, along\nwith the plates.\nBits O\u2019 Business A Detroit\nwholesale firm employing 45\npersons has guaranteed all steady\nwork for the balance of the year,\nexhorts them to \u201cgo out and\nspend, your jobs are secure\u201d\nA cost-conscious publishing firm\ngives key editors a three-minute\n\u201chour glass\u201d to use when mak\ning long-distance calls, as a re\nminder to keep the conversation\nshort... South Florida business\nmen, hotelmen and airlines will\nspend $5 million plugging Flor\nida summer vacations in an ef\nfort to recoup losses from the\nwinter cold spell.\nThe fabrics of spring reflect\nthe loose lines of the season\u2019s\nstyles. There are supple silks,\nmesh woolens as lacy and porous\nas filigree, wools that look like\nknitted string, tweeds with a\nnubby, airier weave, and new\nmohairs as fluffy and light as\nsouffles.\nChecks seem to have emerged\nas spring\u2019s strongest patterns.\nBig, bold ones appear on suits,\ncoats and two-piece ensembles.\nIn color, three families make the\nfashion headlines \u2014reds, oranges\nand greens.,\nSleeves are spreading them\nselves and are wide in form and\nwide in choice. They resemble\ntriangles, lanterns, or puffy pa\nper bags. The width usually be\ngins below a sloping shoulder\nline. All seem to stop short a\nround the elbow.\nHats have a new look \u2014they\nare high, wide, and deep. They\ncover a woman\u2019s head and will\nstay put in a high wind. The\nthree basic shapes are the cloche\nthat hugs the head, the turban,\nand the turned-up roller. The\nfabrics are straw cloth, silks and\nchiffons.\nWomen are really showing\ntheir legs. Hemlines have been\naccelerated by the rounded top\nheavy proportions of the chemise.\nThey are 16 inches from the\nfloor, or shorter. Heels have\nbecome lower and somewhat\nchunkier. They are from li to\n2i inches high. Vamps are much\nlonger. Toes do not look as\nneedle pointed as they did last\nseason. They have a slightly\nrounded tip.\nHandbags run to envelope\nshapes of all sizes. Gloves are\nan important fashion note and\nhave become much longer\nending just below the elbow.\nVan Heflin had a call from\nFrancis D. Lyon in Italy, who\nwants him for his picture \u201cBlue\nMountain,\u201d to be made in Aus\ntralia when he finishes one he\nis currently making in Rome.\nLatest Hollywood twosome:\nGene Kelly and Martha Hyer.\nEsther Williams is plugging for\nJeff Chandler to sign as co-star\nin her \u201cScorpion\u2019s Reef,\u201d to be\nmade in Italy this summer. It\nwas in Italy last year, that Esth\ner and Jeff discovered each\nother.\nWHERE 47 DlEO\u2014Strewn over a muddy field is\nthe wreckage of the Capital Airlines Viscount\nplane that exploded and crashed in flames while\ncoming in for a landing at Tri-City Airport, Mid-\nHANGAR OF DEATH\u2014 Relatives and rescue workers file through the Tri-City Airport, Midland, Mich.,\nin an attempt to Identify the bodies of victims who died when a Capital Airlines Viscount crashed 300\nfeet short of the runway. All 47 aboard the turboprop plane were killed. (International Soundphoto)\nChe\nfor in Thee do I trust;\ncause me to know the way\nwherein I should walk...\u2014\n(Psalm 143, 8.)\nWhen we seek Our Father\u2019s\nguidance in all we do or hope\nto do, surrendering in love\nour will to His, praying not\nonce but many times daily for\nHis direction and then obey\ning without question, we have\nthe wonderful assurance that\nwe will be doing what is right\n\u2014what is best for all con\ncerned.\n--..^Y'S SAjLLRS.._\n\u201cI see you\u2019ve traced your an\ncestors to ths original.\u201d\nMy Neighbors\nBl\u00ae\nQjMw\n\u201cJust like Hungary, Con*\nrade. AU Russian satellites get\nburned up sooner or later!\u201d\nAloahHumskuu.\nHOW/tt T p\nH DOIN'?/\nl/^AR NOAH- IS A\nHOSPITAL REPORT\nCALLED *NEWS OF\nTHE WEAK\nFARRts\nRasKuAMC* S.e.\n\u00a964R. /NOAH IF Tfou\nPLAYEP CARDS WITH\nSANDPAPER BACKS x\nwould you Gnr a\nRaw deal, t\nI, Kay taMn\nland, Mich. AU 47 persons aboard the transport\nwere killed. The plane was en route from New\nYork to Chicago. It was the nation\u2019s worst civil\nian tragedy of 1958. (International Soundphoto)\nNAVY STUDIES CUTBACKS\nThe Chief of Naval Operations\nhas told Congress the Navy\nmight have to lay up more ships\nand close more shore stations to\nconform to a manpower cut.\nAdmiral Arleigh A\u00ab Burke said\nthat by July 1, 1959, the Navy\u2019s\nstrength must be down to 630,-\n000, under present orders, a cut\nof 45,000 in two years. He said\nthe Navy had a critical need for\n675,000 men, and that the cut\nwas being made with extreme\ndifficulty.\nAMERICANS EAT\nHAMBURGER\nThe consumer is the man who,\nsooner or later, will break up\nthis recession. Right now, how\never, he is buying with caution,\nsaving more, trying to get old\nbills paid before he takes on new\ndebts.\nRetailers report buyers are\nwell-heeled but bargain con\nscious; the average consumer is\ndrinking a bit less liquor and\nbuying more hamburger and less\nsteak. He is likely to buy a pair\nof slacks to wear with an old\ncoat, instead of getting a new\nsuit. But, except in the harder\nhit areas, he has been making\nhis regular church contributions.\nGOOD HOUSEKEEPING FOOD SERVICE\nA 301^4 W. College, Tallahassee Phone 3-3408\n^o^ [eft j\nFREE!Over *2OOO in PRIZES!\nj\u00ab^T\u201c^NTTHEBOXES M\niBB\nGRAND PRIZE FREE $<1095\nLARCt* FAMILY FREEZER r\nI\u2014 _ Contest Ends Midnight April 22nd\n10-450.00 Prim 140-440.00 Prizes HUMRY! SIND IN IcTfcV\nFREEZER, UST PRICE $411.95 I FOOD SERVICE PRICE $210.90 T\nMERCHANDISE CHECK $50.00 I MERCHANDISE CHECK. $40.00\nGesHlenwnt 1 wtNb te snbssM my enfw Mi flgeeeMemt I\nBALANCE $30005 I BAUNCE $l9OlO I\n\u25a0\u25a0N\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0l\u25a0\u25a0MM\u25a0\u25a0\u00bbe\u25a0Mmms Mv to teneo\nFOLLOW THESE SIMPLE RuIES: I HAM\nKe Coono\u00df onfooof sobmroo Ao oOmo ko\u00ae afco\u00dfp\u00ae\u00bb FREE ABMKSS\ne wear MHwof pi ommo it HaM w w\nB. O\u00bbIt erne e\u00bbtr\u00bb l\u00abM \u00abM* eentestant, and only 36 PACKAGES C,TY O.P. FWOMf\n4. SteTS L? The -Bl RDS-EYE I den t I\nRHwwBS Will w* OW deewCTWwSS *WI WwOiwOSS, VMI BP ww Haw mF OEb I\nUmi rodopO\u2019 ot oOm cmMjMHRYe fmal. AM e^rh. I PR Q ZEN FOODS MROeMI Oop OumO vooOk\n9. H\u00bbe rtmfatty. newspaper smpleyses, adver. tp any dMWMMt that i aXB. please five directiens te hnmn\nItraewt fem Plan maston are net bins evr Feed Service. I\neRpMe f* e\u00abt\u00ab. 1\nWILL CUTS SABLE WRAP\nLondon, England Mrs. Janie\nAbrahams bequeather one half\nof her sable wrap to each of her\ntwo daughters, in a will made\npublic recently.\n\u201cMother always wanted us to\nhave equal shares of every\nthine.\u201d commented one of the\ndaughters.-\nNEED HELP WITH INCOME TAX\nOR ACCOUNTING PROBLEMS?\nContact Jim Seay\nBOOKKEEPING SERVICE\nTELEPHONE MAIN 7-8808\nTRIP BY JET BARRED\nThe State Department has re\njected a Russian request to let\ntwo Soviet jet airliners land in\nthe New York area with about\n150 members of the famous Moi\nseev Dance Ensemble.\nThe department told the Rus\nsians that it welcomed Soviet\nplans to send the dance troupe\nto this country, but it suggest\ned they \u201cmake arrangements for\ntravel to the United States by\nsome other means.\u201d\nThe reason? In three previous\ninstances, Soviet TU-104 jet lin\ners have been allowed to bring\nSoviet dignitaries to the United\nStates and the landings had in\nvolved special handling. The\ndepartment felt that the dancers\ndid not fall into the same cate\ngory.\nICE CREAM CODE\nThe Food and Drug Adminis\ntration recently issued standards\nfor ice cream. They require 10\nper cent milk fat and limit the\ncontent of air and water. The\nstandards also cover egg ice\ncreams sold as frozen custard,\nFrench ice cream or French cus\ntard ice cream; ice milk, which\nhas been sold as soft ice cream,\nfruit sherberts and water ices.\nThe standards will be tenta\ntive for ninety days, the period\nallowed for interested persons\nto file objections. A final order\nseting the effective date will\nthen be issued.\n3 POLIO SHOTS ENOUGH\nA Committee of experts on\npoliomyelitis has advised the\nPublic Health Service that a\nfourth or \u201cbooster\u201d shot of Salk\nvaccine is not necessary.\nIt said that all evidence point\ned to the effectiveness of the\npresent schedule of three shots.\nthe handsome new\neyeglass hearing aid for men\nYou hear better\u2014and you look your best\u2014when you wear a\nZenith Executive, the world\u2019s handsomest eyeglass hearing aid.\nNew freedom, convenience, versatility. No dangling cords. A high\nperformance hearing aid with 4 wonder transistors. The trimly\nstyled temple-bars fit nearly all standard eyeglass frames, giving\nyou a wide range of frame styles to choose from. Eight other\n4- and S-transistor Zenith models, too. Prices from $5O to $175\nincluding Ten-Day Money-Back Guarantee. Come in... or phone\nfor a free demonstration in the privacy and comfort or your\nhome. No obligation whatsoever.\nZENITH..V^E//o^a^O^ (U&9\nHANDLE BATTERIES AND ACCESSORIES FOR MOST HEARING AIDS\nLtnm, frame frwib, and related profetpontl services in connection witfi Zenith Eyeglass\nMoorios M ar* ovaitoMo only thros<h yew otMMmoiotist, optometrist sr eptlcioa.\nELECTRICAL\nSERVICE\nAnything from wir\ning a house to replac\ning a light bulb\nIke Shepard\nat\nBELL-SHELFER\nFURNITURE CO.\nMAin 7-6543\nRes. MAin 7-3076\nHAULING\nTRUCKING\nAU KINDS\nand Long Distance\nFurniture Insured\nSam Huiley\nS. ADAMS ST.\nMAin 76433","height":"29250","width":"20004"}}
